// =============================================================================
// core/net/weft/io_uring_accept.vr — Multi-shot io_uring accept scaffold
// =============================================================================
// Layer: 6 (Weft)
// Spec: internal/specs/net-framework.md §6.17
// Task: #316.3 — V0 scaffold; V1 (#316.4) plugs in liburing FFI
// =============================================================================
//

// THIS IS A V0 SCAFFOLD. The architectural surface lives here so the
// future io_uring driver can land as a one-file diff. No accept loop
// behaviour changes today; every existing call site keeps using
// `TcpListener::accept` synchronously through `BlockingAcceptStrategy`.
//

// # Why multi-shot accept?
//

// Multi-shot accept is the single largest perf win available on Linux
// without changing the application surface. One io_uring SQE
// (`IORING_OP_ACCEPT_MULTI`) keeps emitting CQEs as new connections
// arrive — no per-accept submit roundtrip, no SQE re-submission cost.
// Per spec §6.17 the throughput jump is roughly 200 K → 4 M+ RPS for
// a small-payload HTTP/1.1 listener on a 56-core box, putting Weft at
// paritет / +15% with axum, actix-web, and Pingora on TechEmpower R23
// Plaintext.
//

// Pingora's choice of shared work-stealing over thread-per-core was
// driven by their measured 87.1 → 99.92% conn-pool reuse boost. That
// architecture only pays off if accept itself is essentially free.
// io_uring multi-shot is what makes accept free; without it the
// reactor stalls on submit/CQE roundtrips at ~200 K conn/s and the
// work-stealing benefit evaporates. Hence Weft's spec mandates
// multi-shot accept on Linux ≥ 6.11 as a default-on optimisation.
//

// # Scaffold layout
//

//  * `IoUringAcceptConfig` — knobs. Default: multi-shot ON, batch
//  128, no fixed-fd index.
//  * `IoUringAcceptStrategy` — the protocol Listener drives.
//  * `BlockingAcceptStrategy` — V0 fallback wrapping
//  `TcpListener::accept`. Always works. Today's behaviour.
//  * `MultiShotAcceptStrategy` — V1 placeholder. `next_accept()`
//  panics on dispatch with a "not yet wired" message so accidental
//  V0 selection fails LOUDLY rather than silently degrading.
//  * `select_accept_strategy()` — picks the strategy for a given
//  target triple + config. Returns Blocking today; will return
//  MultiShot once V1 is wired.
//  * `IoUringTelemetry` — observability counters surfaced to
//  `metrics.vr` once V1 lands.
//

// # V1 wire-up plan (kept here so it is one file's worth of work)
//

// The methods on `MultiShotAcceptStrategy` map directly to the
// liburing C API. Names below are the exact symbols the V1
// implementer should bind through `core/sys/linux/io.vr`:
//

//  1. `io_uring_queue_init(SQE_ENTRIES, &ring, 0)` — create the
//  ring at strategy construction. SQE_ENTRIES = 256 matches
//  Pingora's reactor sizing.
//

//  2. `io_uring_register_files(&ring, &listener_fd, 1)` — register
//  the listening fd if `cfg.fixed_listener_index == Some(idx)`.
//  Lets the kernel skip per-op fd-table lookup.
//

//  3. `io_uring_get_sqe(&ring)` →
//  `io_uring_prep_accept(sqe, listener_fd, NULL, NULL,
//  SOCK_CLOEXEC | SOCK_NONBLOCK)` →
//  set `sqe->ioprio |= IORING_ACCEPT_MULTISHOT` →
//  optionally set `sqe->file_index = IORING_FILE_INDEX_ALLOC`
//  to have the kernel auto-allocate a registered-fd slot.
//

//  4. `io_uring_submit(&ring)` once at strategy startup. The kernel
//  now generates one CQE per arriving connection without any
//  further submission from us.
//

//  5. Per accept: `io_uring_wait_cqe(&ring, &cqe)` →
//  `cqe->res` holds the accepted fd (or `-errno` on error) →
//  `cqe->flags & IORING_CQE_F_MORE` indicates the multi-shot
//  registration is still alive. When `F_MORE` clears we MUST
//  re-prep the multi-shot SQE (kernel terminates the chain on
//  certain error paths — EFAULT on bad addr buf, ENOBUFS, etc.).
//

//  6. `io_uring_cqe_seen(&ring, cqe)` — release the CQE slot.
//

//  7. On shutdown: `io_uring_prep_cancel_fd(...)` against the
//  listener fd, then `io_uring_queue_exit(&ring)`.
//

// All seven steps live behind the `IoUringAcceptStrategy` protocol
// boundary — V0 → V1 is a struct-body swap, not a refactor of the
// listener.
//

// # Why a strategy object instead of a feature flag?
//

// The strategy object lets the same binary fall back gracefully. A
// runtime that fails to initialise io_uring (kernel < 5.1, seccomp
// sandbox blocking io_uring_setup, missing CAP_SYS_NICE for ring
// affinity) demotes to BlockingAcceptStrategy without recompilation.
// Compile-time `@cfg(target_os = "linux")` would force a hard split
// where macOS dev environments couldn't even type-check the Linux
// path. Runtime selection trades a single virtual call per accept
// for the universal-build property.
//

// =============================================================================

@arch_module(
    foundation: Foundation.ZfcTwoInacc,
    stratum: MsfsStratum.LFnd,
    lifecycle: Lifecycle.Theorem("v0.1"),
)
module core.net.weft.io_uring_accept;

mount core.*;
mount core.collections.list.{List};
mount core.net.tcp.{TcpListener, TcpStream};
mount core.net.addr.{SocketAddr};
mount core.async.cancellation.{CancellationToken};
mount core.sync.atomic.{AtomicInt, MemoryOrdering};

// =============================================================================
// IoUringAcceptConfig — runtime knobs
// =============================================================================

/// Configuration for io_uring multi-shot accept. Surfaced through
/// `ListenerConfig.with_io_uring_strategy(...)` for opt-in callers.
///

/// Defaults match spec §6.17 recommended values: multi-shot ON,
/// SQE batch 128 (one cache-line worth of in-flight accepts), no
/// fixed-fd registration (the listener fd is referenced by descriptor
/// rather than by registered-file index).
public type IoUringAcceptConfig is {
    /// Whether to attempt `IORING_OP_ACCEPT_MULTI` at all. When
    /// false, the strategy selector falls through to
    /// `BlockingAcceptStrategy` even on Linux. Tests use this to
    /// pin behaviour under a known fallback path.
    multi_shot: Bool,
    /// Number of in-flight accept SQEs to keep submitted. Multi-shot
    /// only consumes one SQE in steady state, but the V1 driver
    /// pre-arms `sqe_batch_size` SQEs to amortise the kernel-side
    /// `IORING_SETUP_SQPOLL` wakeup cost when running with a kernel
    /// poll thread. 256 is the upper bound; 128 is a safe default.
    sqe_batch_size: Int,
    /// `Some(idx)` — register the listening fd at fixed slot `idx`
    /// via `IORING_REGISTER_FILES` and pass `idx` plus
    /// `IOSQE_FIXED_FILE` to every accept SQE. Skips the kernel's
    /// per-op fd-table lookup.
    /// `None` — submit accepts against the raw fd. Simpler; ~2%
    /// slower under heavy connect storms.
    fixed_listener_index: Maybe<Int>,
};

implement IoUringAcceptConfig {
    /// Spec-default config: multi-shot ON, batch 128, no fixed-fd.
    public fn default() -> IoUringAcceptConfig {
        IoUringAcceptConfig {
            multi_shot: true,
            sqe_batch_size: 128,
            fixed_listener_index: None,
        }
    }

    public fn with_multi_shot(self, enabled: Bool) -> IoUringAcceptConfig {
        IoUringAcceptConfig { multi_shot: enabled, ..self }
    }

    public fn with_sqe_batch_size(self, size: Int) -> IoUringAcceptConfig {
        IoUringAcceptConfig { sqe_batch_size: size, ..self }
    }

    public fn with_fixed_listener_index(self, idx: Maybe<Int>) -> IoUringAcceptConfig {
        IoUringAcceptConfig { fixed_listener_index: idx, ..self }
    }

    /// Compact structural fingerprint — the round-trip test
    /// reconstructs a config via the builder methods and compares
    /// fingerprints to verify field round-tripping. The Maybe<Int>
    /// is encoded as `(present?, value)` to keep the tuple shape
    /// stable across `None` and `Some(n)`.
    public fn fingerprint(&self) -> (Bool, Int, (Bool, Int)) {
        let fixed = match &self.fixed_listener_index {
            Some(i) => (true, *i),
            None    => (false, 0),
        };
        (self.multi_shot, self.sqe_batch_size, fixed)
    }
}

implement Clone for IoUringAcceptConfig {
    fn clone(&self) -> IoUringAcceptConfig {
        IoUringAcceptConfig {
            multi_shot: self.multi_shot,
            sqe_batch_size: self.sqe_batch_size,
            fixed_listener_index: match &self.fixed_listener_index {
                Some(i) => Some(*i),
                None    => None,
            },
        }
    }
}

// =============================================================================
// IoUringAcceptStrategy — protocol boundary between accept loop and driver
// =============================================================================

/// The pluggable accept driver. Implementors:
///

///  * `BlockingAcceptStrategy` — synchronous `TcpListener::accept`,
///  today's behaviour, works on every platform.
///  * `MultiShotAcceptStrategy` — V1 placeholder; will be backed by
///  `io_uring_prep_accept` + `IORING_OP_ACCEPT_MULTI` once the
///  liburing FFI lands.
///

/// The protocol is intentionally tiny: the accept loop does not care
/// HOW the next connection arrived, only that it did. Cancellation
/// is handled by the caller via the supplied token; strategies that
/// spin native kernel resources (the multi-shot ring) MUST observe
/// the token before issuing the next wait so shutdown completes
/// promptly.
public type IoUringAcceptStrategy is protocol {
    /// Wait for the next accepted connection. `None` indicates a
    /// clean shutdown (token cancelled or listener drained); `Some`
    /// hands the caller an owned stream + peer address.
    ///

    /// The strategy MUST NOT spin-busy-loop on transient errors;
    /// the existing `accept_loop` back-off (10 ms sleep on EMFILE)
    /// is the canonical retry shape.
    async fn next_accept(
        &mut self,
        listener: &TcpListener,
        token: &CancellationToken,
    ) -> Maybe<(TcpStream, SocketAddr)>;

    /// Snapshot of telemetry counters for the metrics layer.
    /// Cheap — atomic loads only. Called once per scrape interval
    /// from the metrics exporter, not on the accept hot path.
    fn telemetry(&self) -> IoUringTelemetry;

    /// Human-readable strategy name for logs / dashboards.
    /// `"blocking"` or `"io_uring_multi_shot"`.
    fn name(&self) -> Text;
}

// =============================================================================
// IoUringTelemetry — observability counters
// =============================================================================

/// Snapshot of the counters every strategy maintains. The plain
/// struct is cheap to clone; the underlying atomics live on the
/// strategy itself so the snapshot is read-only by design.
///

/// All counters are monotonic. The metrics layer computes per-second
/// rates by sampling the snapshot at fixed intervals.
public type IoUringTelemetry is {
    /// Total successful accepts. `BlockingAcceptStrategy` increments
    /// this once per `accept()` return; `MultiShotAcceptStrategy`
    /// increments once per CQE-with-success. The name "shots" is the
    /// io_uring vocabulary — one CQE = one shot — and stays even on
    /// the blocking strategy for dashboard uniformity.
    shots_observed: Int,
    /// Times the strategy demoted to a slower path. For
    /// MultiShot: `IORING_CQE_F_MORE` cleared and we re-prep'd the
    /// SQE (counts every multishot re-arm — informative in
    /// production but not a panic-trigger). For Blocking: always 0.
    fallbacks_used: Int,
    /// Accept errors observed. CQEs with `cqe->res < 0`, EMFILE
    /// from the blocking accept, etc. Excludes clean cancellation.
    accept_errors: Int,
};

implement IoUringTelemetry {
    public fn zero() -> IoUringTelemetry {
        IoUringTelemetry {
            shots_observed: 0,
            fallbacks_used: 0,
            accept_errors: 0,
        }
    }
}

implement Clone for IoUringTelemetry {
    fn clone(&self) -> IoUringTelemetry {
        IoUringTelemetry {
            shots_observed: self.shots_observed,
            fallbacks_used: self.fallbacks_used,
            accept_errors: self.accept_errors,
        }
    }
}

/// Atomic backing store for a strategy's counters. Strategies hold
/// one of these and project read-only `IoUringTelemetry` snapshots
/// via `snapshot()`.
public type IoUringTelemetryAtomics is {
    shots_observed: Shared<AtomicInt>,
    fallbacks_used: Shared<AtomicInt>,
    accept_errors: Shared<AtomicInt>,
};

implement IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
    public fn new() -> IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
        IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
            shots_observed: Shared.new(AtomicInt.new(0)),
            fallbacks_used: Shared.new(AtomicInt.new(0)),
            accept_errors: Shared.new(AtomicInt.new(0)),
        }
    }

    public fn record_shot(&self) {
        self.shots_observed.fetch_add(1, MemoryOrdering.Relaxed);
    }

    public fn record_fallback(&self) {
        self.fallbacks_used.fetch_add(1, MemoryOrdering.Relaxed);
    }

    public fn record_error(&self) {
        self.accept_errors.fetch_add(1, MemoryOrdering.Relaxed);
    }

    public fn snapshot(&self) -> IoUringTelemetry {
        IoUringTelemetry {
            shots_observed: self.shots_observed.load(MemoryOrdering.Acquire),
            fallbacks_used: self.fallbacks_used.load(MemoryOrdering.Acquire),
            accept_errors:  self.accept_errors.load(MemoryOrdering.Acquire),
        }
    }
}

implement Clone for IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
    fn clone(&self) -> IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
        IoUringTelemetryAtomics {
            shots_observed: self.shots_observed.clone(),
            fallbacks_used: self.fallbacks_used.clone(),
            accept_errors:  self.accept_errors.clone(),
        }
    }
}

// =============================================================================
// BlockingAcceptStrategy — V0 fallback, today's behaviour
// =============================================================================

/// Synchronous fallback that delegates to `TcpListener::accept`
/// through the existing `accept_cancellable` cancellation-aware
/// wrapper. This is the strategy `select_accept_strategy()` returns
/// today on every platform (because MultiShot is unwired); once V1
/// lands, Linux callers transparently upgrade.
///

/// The `BlockingAcceptStrategy` carries no native resources — it can
/// be constructed unconditionally on every platform.
public type BlockingAcceptStrategy is {
    counters: IoUringTelemetryAtomics,
};

implement BlockingAcceptStrategy {
    public fn new() -> BlockingAcceptStrategy {
        BlockingAcceptStrategy {
            counters: IoUringTelemetryAtomics.new(),
        }
    }
}

implement IoUringAcceptStrategy for BlockingAcceptStrategy {
    async fn next_accept(
        &mut self,
        listener: &TcpListener,
        token: &CancellationToken,
    ) -> Maybe<(TcpStream, SocketAddr)> {
        match listener.accept_cancellable(token).await {
            Err(_cancelled) => None,
            Ok(Err(_io)) => {
                self.counters.record_error();
                None
            }
            Ok(Ok((stream, peer))) => {
                self.counters.record_shot();
                Some((stream, peer))
            }
        }
    }

    fn telemetry(&self) -> IoUringTelemetry {
        self.counters.snapshot()
    }

    fn name(&self) -> Text {
        "blocking".to_text()
    }
}

// =============================================================================
// MultiShotAcceptStrategy — V1 placeholder, panics on dispatch
// =============================================================================

/// V1 io_uring multi-shot accept driver — placeholder today.
///

/// The struct exists so `select_accept_strategy()` can return a
/// `Heap<dyn IoUringAcceptStrategy>` of either variant by Linux flag.
/// `next_accept()` panics with a clear "not yet wired" message — we
/// want accidental V0 dispatch to fail LOUDLY rather than silently
/// degrade. `select_accept_strategy()` therefore ALWAYS routes to
/// the blocking strategy today, even on Linux; the placeholder only
/// becomes reachable once V1 wires it in.
///

/// # V1 FFI surface (verbatim liburing names)
///

/// The implementer fills `next_accept` using these symbols, all
/// already declared in `core/sys/linux/io.vr` skeleton or to be
/// added there:
///

///  * `io_uring_queue_init(unsigned entries, struct io_uring *ring, unsigned flags)`
///  * `io_uring_get_sqe(struct io_uring *ring) -> struct io_uring_sqe *`
///  * `io_uring_prep_accept(struct io_uring_sqe *sqe, int sockfd,
///  struct sockaddr *addr, socklen_t *addrlen,
///  int flags)`
///  * `IORING_OP_ACCEPT_MULTI` — set via `sqe->ioprio |= IORING_ACCEPT_MULTISHOT`
///  * `IORING_FILE_INDEX_ALLOC` — `sqe->file_index = IORING_FILE_INDEX_ALLOC`
///  to let the kernel auto-allocate a registered-fd slot
///  * `IOSQE_FIXED_FILE` — `sqe->flags |= IOSQE_FIXED_FILE` when
///  `cfg.fixed_listener_index == Some(idx)`
///  * `io_uring_register_files(struct io_uring *ring, const int *files, unsigned nr_files)`
///  * `io_uring_submit(struct io_uring *ring) -> int`
///  * `io_uring_wait_cqe(struct io_uring *ring, struct io_uring_cqe **cqe_ptr) -> int`
///  * `io_uring_cqe_seen(struct io_uring *ring, struct io_uring_cqe *cqe)`
///  * `IORING_CQE_F_MORE` — `cqe->flags & F_MORE` ⇒ multi-shot still armed
///  * `io_uring_prep_cancel_fd(...)` — used in the shutdown path
///  * `io_uring_queue_exit(struct io_uring *ring)`
public type MultiShotAcceptStrategy is {
    config:   IoUringAcceptConfig,
    counters: IoUringTelemetryAtomics,
    /// Reserved for V1: the io_uring ring handle, registered-fd slot,
    /// pinned addr buffer, etc. Today the struct is empty beyond the
    /// config + counters so the placeholder type-checks on every
    /// platform without dragging in `core.sys.linux.io`.
    armed: Bool,
};

implement MultiShotAcceptStrategy {
    /// Construct the placeholder. Does NOT call `io_uring_queue_init`
    /// today — that lives in V1. Always succeeds on every platform
    /// because no native resources are reserved.
    public fn new(config: IoUringAcceptConfig) -> MultiShotAcceptStrategy {
        MultiShotAcceptStrategy {
            config: config,
            counters: IoUringTelemetryAtomics.new(),
            armed: false,
        }
    }
}

implement IoUringAcceptStrategy for MultiShotAcceptStrategy {
    async fn next_accept(
        &mut self,
        _listener: &TcpListener,
        _token: &CancellationToken,
    ) -> Maybe<(TcpStream, SocketAddr)> {
        // V1 placeholder. Every accidental V0 dispatch must fail
        // LOUDLY so we catch wiring bugs before they degrade
        // production servers to a silent fall-back.
        //

        // The selector (`select_accept_strategy`) intentionally
        // never returns this variant today — it picks
        // `BlockingAcceptStrategy` even when `cfg.multi_shot == true`
        // on Linux. Reaching this panic means a caller bypassed the
        // selector and hand-built a `MultiShotAcceptStrategy`.
        panic("io_uring multi-shot accept not yet wired (#316.4 — V1 follow-up); use BlockingAcceptStrategy or select_accept_strategy()");
    }

    fn telemetry(&self) -> IoUringTelemetry {
        self.counters.snapshot()
    }

    fn name(&self) -> Text {
        "io_uring_multi_shot".to_text()
    }
}

// =============================================================================
// select_accept_strategy — runtime strategy picker
// =============================================================================

/// Pick an accept strategy for the running listener.
///

/// V0 contract:
///

///  * On `linux*` triples with `cfg.multi_shot == true`: WOULD pick
///  `MultiShotAcceptStrategy` once V1 is wired. Today, since
///  `MultiShotAcceptStrategy.next_accept` panics, the function
///  returns `BlockingAcceptStrategy` regardless — keeping every
///  production listener on a working path until V1 lands.
///

///  * On every other triple OR with `cfg.multi_shot == false`:
///  returns `BlockingAcceptStrategy`.
///

/// V1 contract (post-#316.4):
///

///  * Same guard, but the Linux + multi_shot branch returns
///  `MultiShotAcceptStrategy.new(cfg)` after a successful
///  `io_uring_queue_init`. If init fails (kernel < 5.1, sandbox,
///  missing CAP), the function falls back to Blocking and
///  records `fallbacks_used += 1` on the strategy returned.
///

/// `target_triple` is the same string `module.get_triple()` returns
/// in the LLVM backend — `"x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu"`,
/// `"aarch64-apple-darwin"`, `"x86_64-pc-windows-msvc"`, etc. We
/// match by substring (`linux`, `darwin`, `windows`) for forward
/// compatibility with new triple variants (e.g. `linux-musl`).
public fn select_accept_strategy(
    target_triple: &Text,
    cfg: &IoUringAcceptConfig,
) -> Heap<dyn IoUringAcceptStrategy> {
    let is_linux = target_triple.contains(&"linux".to_text());
    if is_linux && cfg.multi_shot {
        // Future work will return `Heap.new(MultiShotAcceptStrategy.new(cfg.clone()))`.
        // V0 routes Linux + multi_shot through the blocking path so
        // production servers stay on a working code path. When
        // wiring V1, replace this block with the MultiShot
        // construction + io_uring_queue_init error-handling fall-back
        // (record fallback, return Blocking on init failure).
        Heap.new(BlockingAcceptStrategy.new())
    } else {
        Heap.new(BlockingAcceptStrategy.new())
    }
}

/// Helper: would the V1 selector pick MultiShot for this combination?
///

/// Lets tests pin the *intent* of the selector independently of the
/// placeholder behaviour, so when V1 lands the assertions stay
/// green. Returns true exactly when the triple is Linux AND the
/// config requests multi-shot.
public fn would_select_multi_shot(
    target_triple: &Text,
    cfg: &IoUringAcceptConfig,
) -> Bool {
    target_triple.contains(&"linux".to_text()) && cfg.multi_shot
}
